First, let's not calculate the present value of the investment if we use the 10% discount rate.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value} &=\dfrac{\$530}{\left(1 + .10\right)^{1}}+\dfrac{\$690}{\left(1 + .10\right)^{2}}+\dfrac{\$875}{\left(1 + .10\right)^{3}}+\dfrac{\$1,090}{\left(1 + .10\right)^{4}}
\\[10pt]
 &=\$481.818+\$570.247+\$657.4+\$744.484
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$2,453.95}
\end{aligned}$$

**Therefore, after calculating the present value for each period and combining the values, the present value of the investment if we use the 10% discount rate is $2,453.95.**

Next, let's not determine the present value of the investment if we use the 18% discount rate instead.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value} &=\dfrac{\$530}{\left(1 + .18\right)^{1}}+\dfrac{\$690}{\left(1 + .18\right)^{2}}+\dfrac{\$875}{\left(1 + .18\right)^{3}}+\dfrac{\$1,090}{\left(1 + .18\right)^{4}}
\\[10pt]
 &=\$449.152+\$495.547+\$532.562+\$562.232
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$2,039.49}
\end{aligned}$$

**Hence, the present value of the investment if we use the 18% discount rate is $2,039.49.**

Last, let's compute the present value of the investment if we use the 14% discount rate instead.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value} &=\dfrac{\$530}{\left(1 + .24\right)^{1}}+\dfrac{\$690}{\left(1 + .24\right)^{2}}+\dfrac{\$875}{\left(1 + .24\right)^{3}}+\dfrac{\$1,090}{\left(1 + .24\right)^{4}}
\\[10pt]
 &=\$427.419+\$448.751+\$458,093+\$461.04
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$1,796.14}
\end{aligned}$$

**Based on our calculation, the present value of the investment, if we use the 24% discount rate, is $1,796.14.**
